To find a continuation of the given path represented by your 2D array of points, you can use linear extrapolation based on the existing points. Here's an example approach to calculate an additional 10 points:

```java
import java.util.Arrays;

public class PathContinuation {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[][] arr = {{1, 3}, {4, 5}, {6, 7}, {8, 9}}; // Original path
        int numAdditionalPoints = 10;

        // Calculate additional points based on the last two known points
        int[][] newArr = new int[arr.length + numAdditionalPoints][2];

        // Copy original array into new array
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
            newArr[i] = Arrays.copyOf(arr[i], arr[i].length);
        }

        // Use linear extrapolation from the last two known points to generate additional ones
        for (int i = arr.length; i < newArr.length; i++) {
            int xDiff = arr[arr.length - 1][0] - arr[arr.length - 2][0];
            int yDiff = arr[arr.length - 1][1] - arr[arr.length - 2][1];

            // Generate next point by adding differences iteratively 
            newArr[i][0] = newArr[i-1][0] + xDiff;
            newArr[i][1] = newArr[i-1][1] + yDiff;

            System.out.println("Point " + (i+1) + ": (" + 
                newArr[i][0] + ", " +
                newArr[i][1]+ ")");
         }
    }
}
```

This code calculates and prints out an additional ten continuation points based on a simple linear extrapolation from the last two existing coordinates in your original path. Adjustments may be needed depending on how you want to define continuity or if more complex paths are involved.

