2. **Create an Endpoint in Your Java Backend**:
   Use the AWS SDK for Java to create an endpoint that fetches files from S3. Here’s a simple example:

   ```java
   @GetMapping("/file/{key}")
   public ResponseEntity<byte[]> getFile(@PathVariable String key) {
       AmazonS3 s3Client = AmazonS3ClientBuilder.standard().build();
       S3Object s3Object = s3Client.getObject(new GetObjectRequest("YOUR_BUCKET_NAME", key));
       InputStream inputStream = s3Object.getObjectContent();

       byte[] content = IOUtils.toByteArray(inputStream);

       return ResponseEntity.ok()
               .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_OCTET_STREAM)
               .body(content);
   }
   ```

This code retrieves the file as bytes and sends it back as a response.

4. **Fetch File in Your React App**:
In your React component, use `axios` or `fetch` API to call this endpoint and retrieve the file data.

```javascript
import axios from 'axios';
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

function FilePreview({ fileKey }) {
  const [fileData, setFileData] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchFile = async () => {
      try {
        const response = await axios.get(`/file/${fileKey}`, { responseType: 'arraybuffer' });
        const base64String = btoa(
          new Uint8Array(response.data).reduce((data, byte) => data + String.fromCharCode(byte), '')
        );

        setFileData(`data:application/pdf;base64,${base64String}`);
      } catch (error) {
        console.error('Error fetching file:', error);
      }
    };

    fetchFile();
  }, [fileKey]);

  return (
    <div>
      {fileData ? (
        <iframe src={fileData} width="600" height="400" title="PDF Preview"></iframe>
      ) : (
        <p>Loading...</p>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}

export default FilePreview;
